# 2026-03-02 (cont. 4 — decoder refactor + Register enum)

Refactored decoder tests and designed the Register enum.

## What Was Built

* DecoderTests.cs — refactored all 3 tests to pass byte[] instead of single byte. Killed premature 2-arg ModR/M test. Added new red test: Decode([0x00, 0xC8]) asserting resolved operands (Operation=Add, Destination=Register.AL, Source=Register.CL).
* Register.cs — enum with all 16 registers. Order is intentional: AL(0)–BH(7) then AX(8)–DI(15). Mirrors Intel's REG encoding table exactly — the 3-bit REG/R/M index maps directly to the enum value, with W bit as an offset of 8. Resolution is just `regIndex + (word ? 8 : 0)`, no switch needed.
* Decoder.Decode signature changed from `byte` to `byte[]`.
* Opcode00Tests skipped via `[Fact(Skip=...)]` to focus on decoder unit tests.
* Re-downloaded 00.json.gz test data (was lost between machines).

## Key Decisions

+ Register enum ordering matches Intel REG table — enum value IS the lookup index. W=0 uses values 0–7 (8-bit), W=1 uses values 8–15 (16-bit). Eliminates need for a switch/dictionary to resolve register names.
+ DecodedInstruction will carry resolved Source and Destination (Register type) not raw MOD/REG/R/M fields. Execute should not re-interpret encoding tables.
+ Decoder accepts byte[] and consumes what it needs. No fixed-arity overloads.

## Resolved

+ Operand representation — Register enum for register operands. Memory and immediate representations still TBD.
+ Decoder input format — byte[] matching the test suite's int[] (cast on entry).

## In Progress

? DecodedInstruction needs Source and Destination properties of type Register.
? Decoder.Decode needs to parse byte 2 (ModR/M) for the MOD=11 case — shift/mask to extract REG and R/M, resolve via enum offset.
? Memory and immediate operand representation still unresolved — will surface when tests demand it.

