# 2025-03-02 (cont. 1 — design decisions)

Resolved all open questions from project inception through discussion.

## Design Decisions

+ Register overlap modeling — 16-bit registers (AX, BX, CX, DX) are source of truth. 8-bit halves (AH/AL, BH/BL, CH/CL, DH/DL) are computed properties via mask/shift. Rationale: addressing modes only use 16-bit registers; 8-bit operands pay a trivial bitwise cost.
+ Flags representation — 16-bit FLAGS register is source of truth. Individual flag bools (CF, PF, AF, ZF, SF, OF, TF, IF, DF) are computed properties. Matches test suite format (ushort) and keeps instruction logic readable. May pivot later as understanding deepens.
+ Memory model — separate class with ReadByte/WriteByte methods, not a raw array on Cpu. Bus cycle tracking will eventually add behavior to memory access; having the seam in place now avoids a painful refactor later.
+ Accuracy target — instruction-level first (initial -> final state comparison), tighten to cycle-level later. Cycle-level requires modeling BIU/EU cooperation, prefetch queue timing, and T-state sequencing — defer until opcodes are passing.

